        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer323799011" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4338108032381822209">I wonder who would be more disappointed: the person who picked up this book thinking they were reading <i>Fifty Shades of Gray </i> or vice versa.<br/><br/>This book isn&apos;t easy to rate. I like the basic premise of needing forgiveness and closure and the Wilmington/ Holden Beach setting. However, it seemed as if there were too many subplots, irrelevant details, and overwritten emotional appeal. My college creative writing prof would have crossed out over half of it.<br/><br/>People who enjoy Kingsbury&apos;s other novels will e</span>
  <span id="freeText4338108032381822209" style="display:none">I wonder who would be more disappointed: the person who picked up this book thinking they were reading <i>Fifty Shades of Gray </i> or vice versa.<br /><br />This book isn't easy to rate. I like the basic premise of needing forgiveness and closure and the Wilmington/ Holden Beach setting. However, it seemed as if there were too many subplots, irrelevant details, and overwritten emotional appeal. My college creative writing prof would have crossed out over half of it.<br /><br />People who enjoy Kingsbury's other novels will enjoy this one also. I could have identified the author without being told in advance.<br /><br />Update: I just read some other GR reviews of this book, and they call it "well-rounded." I'm not sure how they can call a CLEARLY pro-life book unbiased. I will agree, however, that Kingsbury dealt with the issue with sensitivity.<br /></span>
